    <title>Combined summary - BIP Proposal: Wallet Labels Export Format</title>
    <updated>2023-06-16T00:08:32.961930+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2022-September/020940.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>A Bitcoin Improvement Proposal (BIP) has been introduced by Craig Raw to standardize the export and import of labels attached to transactions, addresses, inputs, and outputs in a wallet. The proposed format utilizes the comma-separated values (CSV) format that can be compressed using the ZIP format and optionally encrypted using AES. The aim is to make manual or bulk management of labels accessible to users without technical expertise while retaining wide accessibility and reducing file size. Feedback on the proposal is requested, and a reference implementation is yet to be determined.Craig has proposed transferring and managing labels between different wallet implementations and applications through his BIP. His proposal includes a standardization of the export and import of labels using a simple two-column CSV file format, which can be compressed using ZIP and optionally encrypted using AES. There is some tension between the goals of transferring and managing labels in applications outside Bitcoin wallets, with some arguing that achieving both goals may be too difficult. Craig acknowledges the feedback and plans to make changes to the proposal in future iterations.Suggestions have been made to write inputs and outputs as descriptors, merge Inputs and Outputs into one classification called just "Outputs," remove unnecessary types that can cause privacy issues, and mandate double-quoting all fields. There are concerns about the security of the ZIP encryption standard used for encrypting the CSV file. Ali Sherief suggested merging Inputs and Outputs into one classification called just "Outputs" because no wallet software labels outputs. Christopher Allen expressed interest in seeing some separation of layers regarding output formats and has been working on an export to a Plain-Text Accounting-friendly format using the beancount python app. The final tool will allow users to get any transactions from a descriptor from a random explora via Tor and then get price information from a random spotbit price server via Tor. It will then export a beancount compatible file. Allen hopes that this idea will inspire others working on the wallet export format. The proposed BIP seeks to create a standard for the export and import of labels from a wallet, making it easier for users to move between different wallets. The proposal provides valuable guidance in spending to avoid undesirable leaks of private information and has even become mandatory when spending in several Bitcoin wallets. Overall, the proposed BIP for a standardized format to export and import labels from a wallet aims to ensure that users do not experience lock-in to a particular wallet application by using common formats. Feedback on the proposal is appreciated.The email thread from the Bitcoin-dev mailing list discusses a new proposed feature for the Bitcoin protocol called "Schnorr signatures" which aims to improve transaction privacy and efficiency. Schnorr signatures are an alternative to the current signature algorithm used in Bitcoin, ECDSA. They offer benefits such as smaller signatures, faster verification times, and improved privacy through the ability to create multi-signature transactions without revealing the identities of the signers. The Bitcoin-dev mailing list is a forum for discussion among developers working on the Bitcoin protocol. It is hosted by the Linux Foundation and allows developers to share ideas, propose changes, and collaborate on improving the functionality and security of the Bitcoin network.</summary>
